# Product direction

* This repository is being reshaped into a Windows 11 x64 desktop Markdown viewer. Treat legacy Zed editor behavior as source material, not as a product requirement.
* Target only x86_64 Windows 11. macOS, Linux, WSL, web, and mobile are out of scope.
* When touching platform abstractions, prefer simplifying them toward Windows-only code instead of preserving cross-platform layers.
* Use pure Rust and GPUI. Do not add JavaScript, TypeScript, Node.js tooling, WebView, Electron, Tauri, or any second UI framework.
* Optimize for fast startup, low memory use, and smooth scrolling. Prefer direct code paths over extensible architecture.

# Feature guardrails

* The app is read-only. Never add document editing, caret movement, text mutation, save flows, undo or redo, code actions, completions, or any other editor behavior.
* The app is single-purpose. Do not add IDE or workstation features such as LSP, git tooling, terminals, collaboration, AI surfaces, project management, or extension systems unless the user explicitly asks for a viewing-specific need.
* Every feature must directly improve Markdown viewing. Acceptable scope is opening files, reloading files, navigating rendered content, zoom, scrolling, theming, and other clearly read-only behavior.
* Prefer rendered Markdown as the main UI. Avoid split editor or preview designs and avoid modes that expose raw text editing as a primary workflow.
* If legacy Zed code conflicts with these constraints, remove or bypass it rather than adapting the viewer around editor assumptions.

# Implementation guidelines

* Keep changes minimal and local. Prefer deleting unused editor infrastructure over wrapping it in compatibility layers.
* Prefer implementing functionality in existing files unless a new module is a clear standalone viewer concern.
* Prioritize correctness and clarity first, then performance work that materially improves startup, parsing, layout, or scrolling.
* Do not write organizational comments that restate what the code already says. Comments should explain only non-obvious reasons.
* Avoid panic-prone code such as unwrap, expect, unchecked indexing, or assuming optional UI state exists.
* Never silently discard fallible results. Propagate or surface errors with context.
* User-visible failures such as file IO, Markdown parse errors, or image loading problems must surface in the UI in a simple Windows-friendly way.
* Use full words for variable names. Avoid abbreviations that hide intent.
* Avoid creative additions. If a capability is not required for opening and reading Markdown, leave it out.

# GPUI guidelines

* Use GPUI for windowing, rendering, focus, and app state. Do not introduce another UI or event framework.
* Keep the foreground thread focused on input, layout, and painting. Move file IO and Markdown parsing off the UI thread when they may block.
* When async work updates UI state, use GPUI entity patterns correctly and notify after view-relevant state changes.
* Prefer straightforward view state flow: source file to parsed Markdown model to rendered GPUI elements.
* Avoid background services that stay alive without clear viewer value.

# Testing guidance

* In GPUI tests that rely on run_until_parked, prefer GPUI executor timers over smol::Timer::after so timing stays visible to GPUI's scheduler.
* New tests and manual verification should focus on Windows behavior, including file opening, scrolling, DPI scaling, reload behavior, and read-only guarantees.
* Do not spend effort maintaining cross-platform snapshots, non-Windows feature flags, or macOS or Linux specific test paths.

# Windows-specific guidance

* Assume Windows 11 conventions for file dialogs, paths, keyboard shortcuts, fonts, window behavior, and packaging.
* Do not spend effort on cross-platform keybindings, path normalization, documentation variants, or conditional compilation for non-Windows targets.
* Prefer Windows-native integrations when they simplify the viewer and do not compromise the pure Rust plus GPUI requirement.

# Rules hygiene

* Keep this file high-signal and specific to recurring traps in this Windows Markdown viewer codebase.
* Prefer concrete constraints over architecture tours.
* Add new rules only when they capture a real failure mode or recurring mistake.
